            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.IX.R11</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>And Tips spirit, and his father&rsquo;s Christian spirit</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-d240c543-7fff-dd8a-907c-1a96abd24393\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Tip&rsquo;s manifestation of the &ldquo;spirit&rdquo; is anger at Clennam for not advancing him money. Mr. Dorrit&rsquo;s anger is directed at Tip, not for insulting Mr. Clennam, but for the implied insult to himself that, in receiving a refusal of money, he &ldquo;received treatment not due to a gentleman&rdquo; (LD 370). Mr. Dorrit will suggest that Tip is lacking in &ldquo;Christian&rdquo; duty in not trying Clennam again.&nbsp;</p>"
